All that didn't happen for the obvious reason that Santa Claus is not real. He is merely a fictional character who pops up every Christmas to spread the cheer, especially for kids, with his bagful of gifts. The Christmas season and the catastrophic year 2020 is now behind us. With the New Year finally here, allow me to indulge in some wishful thinking as far as what Kenyan sport can look forward to in 2021.
So here goes my wish list for Kenyan sports in the New Year:
Clean sport





In recent times, the bane of Kenyan sports has been the increasing cases of top performing athletes who have been caught for doping.
Never before has Kenya’s status and credentials as a global powerhouse been so closely scrutinised than the present times, all thanks to a few rotten apples. All that could change in 2021.
The signing of the Anti-Doping (Amendment) Bill, 2020 into law by President Uhuru Kenyatta on the eve of New Year may just stem the doping tide in Kenya.
Other than its punitive nature, the new law has paved the way for Kenyan athletes to not just participate in major international events, but also compete clean in what should be an action-packed year.
Reversal of Covid damage
This is a dicey one, given that 2020 — to borrow Education Cabinet Secretary Prof George Magoha’s words — was a lost year for sports, not just in Kenya, but across the world.



